  {
    "id": "sylvia",
    "name": "Sylvia Rappaport",
    "partners": [
      "Seymour Feldman",
      "Sol Rappaport"
    ],
    "generation": "A",
    "branch": "Sylvia",
    "parent": null,
    "vitals": {
      "photo": "sylvia.jpg",
      "location": "Lauderhill, FL",
      "deceased": true,
      "dateOfBirth": "1923-09-04",
      "dateOfDeath": "2004-10-17",
      "obituary": "Sylvia \"Sippy\" Rappaport (née Warshawsky) was born on September 4, 1923 in Newark, New Jersey, the daughter of Rose and Lou Warshawsky. She grew up in a large, lively household full of siblings, cousins, singing, and dancing — a childhood she remembered with pure joy. \"I guess we were poor,\" she wrote, \"but we had all the nicest things: plenty of food, lots of love, attention, and so many dear brothers and sisters.\"\n\nAt 16, she met Seymour \"Butch\" Feldman — the best athlete and best-looking boy in the class, she always said. They fell in love, and when Seymour was drafted into the Army Signal Corps during World War II, Sippy married him in 1942 and followed him from Texas to Louisiana to Tennessee to Missouri, building their life together wherever the Army sent them. When Seymour shipped overseas to the Pacific, Sippy returned home and waited — and when he came back, she said, \"we were so happy, so in love, so lucky to be alive.\"\n\nThey built a beautiful home in Maplewood, New Jersey and raised four children — Sidney, Paul, Craig, and Carol Sue. Then in 1961, Seymour was diagnosed with Acute Leukemia and died within weeks, leaving Sippy a widow at 38. She never stopped. She opened a clothing boutique out of her basement, co-founded the Seymour Feldman Leukemia Fund that raised money for research for 40 years, drove her children to every ball game, Hebrew school, and dental appointment, and kept her home filled with love and life. \"I still had too much time to grieve,\" she wrote — so she stayed busy, stayed present, and stayed strong.\n\nIn 1974, she found love again with Sol Rappaport, a warm and devoted man who cherished her. Together they traveled the world — Japan, Hong Kong, Thailand, Europe, Canada, the American Southwest, and many summers between their homes in New Jersey and Lauderhill, Florida. Sol loved golf and his computer; Sippy loved Mah Jongg, Canasta, long walks, and cooking for anyone who walked through the door. Their home was always open.\n\nShe outlived more than any grandmother should ever have to — her beloved son Sidney, her son Craig, who lost his battle with Leukemia before her, and others she loved deeply. Through every loss she found her way back: to joy, to family, to the Passover Seder table she loved to set for everyone, to the Warshawsky Family Circle that met every year for decades.\n\nOn April 15, 2004, at the age of 80, Sippy sat down and wrote her memoir by hand — in a book given to her by her granddaughter Julie — addressed to her children, grandchildren, and \"future great-grandchildren, even further into the future.\" She closed with these words:\n\n\"Suppose, as you are all reading this story of my memories, you think I've had a horrible and difficult life. That is not true. You do go through hard times, but I have had a wonderful life. I truly feel that life, happiness, and the greatest of blessings come from my grandchildren. What could I have done without them?\"\n\nShe signed it simply: Your Grandma Sippy."
    },
